    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to the style of architecture, interior design, and decorative arts that prevailed in the United States, ca. 1870 to ca. 1925. As a result of the ever widening influence of the Arts and Crafts Movement in England, the Craftsman style was also based on the rejection of historical styles in favor of a traditional simplicity. Many of the same types of people were involved, such as social reformers, teachers and women's organizations, architects, and designers, as well as the prophets of the movement, John Ruskin and William Morris. In architecture, the style is characterized by modest homes, such as the bungalow, and simple treatment of materials.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000048185/Mendelowitz, A History of American Art (1970)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指大約流行於西元1870年至1925年的美國建築、室內設計與裝飾藝術風格。由於英國工藝美術運動（Arts and Crafts Movement）的影響與日俱增，工藝師風格的基礎也建立在排斥歷史性風格，而崇尚傳統的簡單樸實。許多類似社群的人都參與這個運動，包括社會改革者、教師及婦女團體、建築師、設計師，以及該運動最重要的的提倡者約翰‧羅斯金（John Ruskin）和威廉‧莫里斯（William Morris）。建築方面，此風格以樸實的住家為特色，例如單樓層的平房，並以簡單的方式處理建築材料。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
